description:
Official Solicitation

One of the hottest selling characters of 2002 comes home to Blue Water Productions and Alias Enterprises! Trapped 5,000 years out of time, the would-be Egyptian Goddess, Isis, must adjust to her new life in 21st century Los Angeles. Using her mystical staff and some help from a few new friends, Isis will protect those around her from evil that may threaten their world. But how can she protect a world that she doesn't fully understand? Join Isis in her ongoing series debut issue, as she's introduced to the modern world and its new ways of life. But it seems Isis is not the only ancient warrior alive in our time - as she must battle the Mummy of Sekhent upon her awakening from the dead! Optioned by Grammnet Entertainment at PARAMOUNT PICTURES!
name: Legend of Isis

description:
Numbering continued from Top-Notch Comics #27; becomes Laugh Comix with issue #46.

The Wizard, the Man with the Super Brain, Roy the Super Boy and the Black Hood having proved not to be the as successful as MLJ hoped for in the superhero department, with the 28th issue they changed the title from Top-Notch Comics to Top-Notch Laugh Comics, changing the line-up as well.

The only one of the original mystery men to remain was the Black Hood, the rest of the comic was replaced with a line-up humor strips including, Snoop McGook a dim-witted detective, Pokey Oakey a rip-off of L‘il Abner, Suzie, with good-girl art about a girl who can’t seem to find a job, Senor Siesta the “humorous” adventures of a stereotypical Mexican, the Three Monkeyteers, a rip-off of the 3 Stooges as monkeys, Percy a high school student and the hopelessly twisted Gloomy Gus: the Homeless Ghost, about a ghost that Heaven won’t let in, and Hell doesn’t want, who wants another body, each of his adventures involves him possessing some hapless victim and messing up trying to life their life until he gets that body killed. Also was Dotty & Ditto, a little girl in the Wild West and her talking parrot.
name: Top-Notch Laugh Comics

While numbered 5 - 7, there were really only 3 issues of Jetta: Teen age Sweetheart of the 21st Century, at this time in their history Standard was numbering their new comics starting at a higher number.

The art on all three issues was done by Dan Decarlo, who shortly after this would go to MLJ (Archie) where he would redesign all the characters with his style becoming the standard for more than 50 years thereafter.

description:
In 1942, during world war II, Ralston-Purina revived their comic book premium featuring silent film star Tom Mix changing the title to Tom Mix Commandos Comics while keeping the number of their first 9 “books and with Tom and his partners trading in their cowboy outfits for solider attire.”

The stories however became progressively stranger as Tom and his commandos dealt with invisible, and giant Nazi, and dragon riding Japanese.
name: Tom Mix Commandos Comics
